ies can lead to more accurate and reliable models for protective behavior detection, which is crucial in healthcare applications. This research will advance the field of multimodal data fusion and provide practical solutions for real-world scenarios.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nOptimizing statistical weighting strategies involves addressing complex interactions between different modalities and context-specific variations. Naive approaches may fail to capture these nuances, leading to suboptimal performance. Technical challenges include developing sophisticated algorithms that can dynamically adjust weights and handle large-scale datasets.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on basic statistical weighting strategies, but the complexity of optimizing these strategies has not been fully addressed. Additionally, the integration of additional modalities and the handling of specific cases have not been thoroughly explored. This research aims to fill these gaps by developing advanced algorithms and frameworks.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology includes:\n- Developing a dynamic statistical weighting strategy using reinforcement learning.\n- Integrating additional modalities (e.g., audio, physiological signals) into the multimodal fusion framework.\n- Conducting a detailed analysis to understand specific cases where mean weighting outperforms statistical weighting.\n- Evaluating the proposed methods on the EmoPain dataset and other datasets to assess generalizability.\n- Developing a transfer learning framework to improve model performance across different datasets.\n\nExpected outcomes include:\n- Improved accuracy and reliability in protective behavior detection.\n- A more sophisticated understanding of multimodal data fusion and statistical weighting strategies.\n- Practical solutions for real-world healthcare applications.", role='assistant'