ed into LSTM models to improve their performance in multimodal configurations for protective behavior detection?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nAddressing this problem is crucial for advancing the field of multimodal data fusion and improving the accuracy and reliability of protective behavior detection models. Enhancing LSTM models with statistical weighting can lead to more robust and effective healthcare solutions, while also providing insights into the generalizability of statistical weighting across different types of models.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nIntegrating statistical weighting into LSTM models is challenging due to the complex nature of LSTM architectures and the need to balance accuracy with interpretability. Naive approaches may fail to capture the nuances of multimodal data and could lead to overfitting or reduced model performance.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has primarily focused on statistical weighting in dual-modality configurations and CNN models. The challenge of applying statistical weighting to LSTM models and ensuring interpretability has not been fully addressed, leading to gaps in the literature.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology involves developing a framework that integrates statistical weighting with attention mechanisms in LSTM models. The EmoPain dataset will be used for training and validation. Key metrics include accuracy, F1 score, and interpretability. The expected outcomes are improved performance of LSTM models in multimodal configurations and enhanced interpretability of the models."}

