ions and modalities.\n   - Explore the use of machine learning algorithms to automatically determine optimal weights for each modality.\n\n2. **Integration of Additional Modalities:**\n   - Incorporate audio and visual data to create a more comprehensive multimodal model.\n   - Develop frameworks that can dynamically adjust to the inclusion of new modalities.\n\n3. **Enhancing Explainability:**\n   - Implement techniques like SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) to provide more detailed insights into model decisions.\n   - Develop visualization tools that help clinicians and researchers understand the model's reasoning process.\n\n4. **Handling Variability in Data:**\n   - Investigate robust statistical methods that can handle variations in data scale and distribution.\n   - Develop models that are invariant to changes in data scale, ensuring reliability in real-world scenarios.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe research aims to enhance the detection of protective behaviors in pain patients using multimodal data fusion. While existing approaches using statistical weighting and human-centered segmentation show promise, there are opportunities to optimize these methods, integrate additional data types, improve model explainability, and ensure robustness to data variability.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nMachine learning, particularly in the context of multimodal data fusion, holds significant potential for improving the detection of protective behaviors in pain patients. By leveraging advanced statistical weighting techniques and integrating additional data types, models can achieve higher accuracy and reliability.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we optimize statistical weighting strategies in multimodal data fusion to further enhance the detection of protective behaviors in pain patients?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting a