odels to improve their performance in multimodal configurations.\n   - Develop a framework that combines statistical weighting with attention mechanisms in LSTM models.\n\n2. **Comparative Analysis of Statistical Weighting Across Models:**\n   - Conduct a comprehensive comparative analysis of statistical weighting across different types of models (e.g., CNNs, LSTMs, RNNs) to understand its generalizability.\n   - Explore the impact of different statistical weighting strategies (e.g., Bayesian weighting, entropy-based weighting) on model performance.\n\n3. **Interpretable Multimodal Models:**\n   - Develop interpretable multimodal models that leverage statistical weighting while maintaining explainability.\n   - Integrate techniques from causal inference to enhance the interpretability of the models.\n\n4. **Human-Centered Design in Multimodal Segmentation:**\n   - Further refine the human-centered approach to modality segmentation to optimize model performance.\n   - Develop guidelines or frameworks for human-centered modality segmentation in multimodal data fusion.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe collective ideas focus on enhancing the performance of LSTM models with statistical weighting, conducting a comparative analysis of statistical weighting across different models, developing interpretable multimodal models, and refining human-centered modality segmentation.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nMultimodal data fusion and statistical weighting strategies significantly enhance the performance of models in protective behavior detection, particularly in healthcare applications. However, there is a need to explore how these techniques can be effectively applied to different types of models and to ensure that the models remain interpretable and explainable.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can statistical weighting be effectively integrat